This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with sentiment analysis, which is a subfield of natural language processing. The paper also discusses the use of machine learning techniques for sentiment analysis, which falls under the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper involves the use of feature extraction techniques, which is a common topic in the sub-category of cs.IR (Information Retrieval). The use of classifiers such as logistic regression, support vector machines, K-nearest neighbors, decision tree, and Bernoulli Naive Bayes also suggests that the paper could belong to the sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Finally, the paper's focus on analyzing text data could also place it in the sub-category of cs.CY (Computers and Society).
